abstract: The details of millions of Iranian bank cards were published online after antigovernment protests last month. Experts suspect a state-sponsored cyberattack.
snippet: The details of millions of Iranian bank cards were published online after antigovernment protests last month. Experts suspect a state-sponsored cyberattack.
lead_paragraph: After demonstrators in Iran set fire to hundreds of bank branches last month in antigovernment protests, the authorities dealt with another less visible banking threat that is only now coming to fuller light: a security breach that exposed the information of millions of Iranian customer accounts.

abstract: The visit of Sergey Lavrov to Washington came at a delicate moment in the relationship between President Trump and Russia.
snippet: The visit of Sergey Lavrov to Washington came at a delicate moment in the relationship between President Trump and Russia.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Secretary of State Mike Pompeo warned Moscow not to interfere in American elections while meeting on Tuesday with Sergey V. Lavrov, Russia’s foreign minister. But Mr. Lavrov denounced accusations of election interference and said the Trump administration still had not unveiled proof of nefarious Russian activity.

abstract: A surge in searches for the definition of an old-school pronoun signals a new, nonbinary meaning.
snippet: A surge in searches for the definition of an old-school pronoun signals a new, nonbinary meaning.
lead_paragraph: Merriam-Webster announced the pronoun “they” as its word of the year on Tuesday, marking the rise of the use of the venerable plural pronoun to refer to a single person whose gender identity is nonbinary.

abstract: Russian Foreign Minister Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov on Tuesday said Moscow wanted to publish a cache of communications with Washington that he said cleared Russia of allegations it interfered in the 2016 U.S. election, but that the United States has blocked their release.

abstract: Former FBI attorney Lisa Page, who came under fire from President Donald Trump and other Republicans for sending text messages that disparaged Trump during the 2016 presidential campaign, on Tuesday sued her former employer over what she called "unlawful disclosure of information about her to the media."

abstract: Ethiopia's federal police were deployed to universities across the country on Tuesday, the government said, as authorities sought to calm ethnic tensions which have claimed the lives of seven students in the past three months.

lead_paragraph: ADDIS ABABA — Ethiopia's federal police were deployed to universities across the country on Tuesday, the government said, as authorities sought to calm ethnic tensions which have claimed the lives of seven students in the past three months.
headline_main: Ethiopia Deploys Police in Universities to Stop Ethnic Violence
headline_print_headline: Ethiopia Deploys Police in Universities to Stop Ethnic Violence

abstract: After months of political wrangling, House Democrats agreed Tuesday to President Donald Trump’s revamped version of a 25-year-old North American free trade agreement. But they pried some concessions out of the Trump administration before saying they’d go along.

lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — After months of political wrangling, House Democrats agreed Tuesday to President Donald Trump’s revamped version of a 25-year-old North American free trade agreement. But they pried some concessions out of the Trump administration before saying they’d go along.
headline_main: Democrats Agree to North America Trade Pact: What's in It?

abstract: Tired of San Francisco streets being used as a testing ground for the latest delivery technology and transportation apps, city leaders are now requiring businesses to get permits before trying out new high-tech ideas in public.
snippet: Tired of San Francisco streets being used as a testing ground for the latest delivery technology and transportation apps, city leaders are now requiring businesses to get permits before trying out new high-tech ideas in public.
lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Tired of San Francisco streets being used as a testing ground for the latest delivery technology and transportation apps, city leaders are now requiring businesses to get permits before trying out new high-tech ideas in public.
headline_main: Testing Tech Ideas in Public? San Francisco Says Get Permit
headline_print_headline: Testing Tech Ideas in Public? San Francisco Says Get Permit

abstract: A new law would give the country’s 1.3 billion people more power over data collected by companies but allow the government to exempt itself from the rules.
snippet: A new law would give the country’s 1.3 billion people more power over data collected by companies but allow the government to exempt itself from the rules.
lead_paragraph: MUMBAI, India — India is poised to pass its first major data protection law, placing new restrictions on how corporations can collect and use information from the country’s 1.3 billion people.
